onships. Situating millennials’ lives within contemporary social and cultural conditions in the United States, Intimate Inequalities takes an intersectional approach to examining how millennials challenge—or rather, uphold—social inequalities in their lives as they come into their own as full adults. Intimate Inequalities provides an in-depth look into the intimate lives of one group of millennials living in the United States, demystifying what actually goes on behind closed doors, and arguing that millennials’ private lives can reveal much about their ability to navigate inequalities in their lives more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGeneration YzUnited StatesxSocial life and customs. 0aInterpersonal relationszUnited States. 0aIntimacy (Psychology) 0aIntimacy (Psychology). 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh  aMillenial, Millenial relationships, modern relationship, relationships, romantic relationships, gender, social class, sexuality, LGBTQ, college, college students, hook up, sex, college sex, religion, college religion, evangelical, purity, virgin, intimacy, dating, friendship, romance, relationship, age, marriage, adult dating, race in dating.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2021 Englishz978311075406308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2021z9783110753950oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882393840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978823938423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978823938/original  a978-3-1